ssented%20in%2030%20years.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPowell%2C%20for%20his%20part%2C%20has%20continued%20to%20insist%20that%20the%20Fed%20is%20still%20%26quot%3Ba%20ways%20away%20from%20seeing%20where%20things%20settle%20down%2C%26quot%3B%20regarding%20President%20Donald%20Trump's%20tariffs%20and%20the%20impact%20on%20inflation.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EYet%2C%20two%20members%20of%20the%20Federal%20Open%20Market%20Committee%20disagreed%2C%20and%20on%20Friday%2C%20they%20each%20released%20statements%20unpacking%20their%20views.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EGovernor%20Christopher%20Waller%20and%20Vice%20Chair%20for%20Supervision%20Michelle%20Bowman%20have%20both%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Frate-cuts-july-fed-meeting-bowman-goolsbee-inflation-trump-tariffs-2025-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Epreviously%20advocated%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20cutting%20interest%20rates%2C%20and%20reiterated%20their%20views%20at%20this%20week's%20meeting.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBoth%20expressed%20concern%20regarding%20the%20US%20labor%20market%2C%20and%20newly%20released%20data%20may%20back%20up%20their%20claims.%20The%20nonfarm%20payroll%20report%20on%20Friday%20showed%20that%20the%20US%20economy%20added%2073%2C000%20jobs%20in%20July%2C%20fewer%20than%20expected.%20May%20and%20June%20also%20saw%20figures%20revised%20lower%20by%20a%20combined%20258%2C000%2C%20pointing%20to%20a%20weakening%20labor%20market.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHere's%20why%20the%20two%20Fed%20governors%20say%20the%20Fed%20need%20to%20cut%20rate.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22936d533d-7d38-4df3-97cd-28b920fa2f5b%5C%22%3EWaller's%20argument%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWidely%20considered%20a%20likely%20candidate%20to%20replace%20Powell%20as%20chairman%20of%20the%20Fed%2C%20Waller%20has%20been%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffinterest-rate-cuts-federal-reserve-trump-powell-inflation-economy-outlook-2025-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Eoutspoken%20critic%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20decision%20not%20to%20cut%20interest%20rates%20this%20year.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20his%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.federalreserve.gov%2Fnewsevents%2Fspeech%2Fwaller20250801a.htm%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edissenting%20opinion%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20he%20reiterated%20the%20argument%20that%20reducing%20it%20by%2025%20basis%20points%20made%20sense.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWaller%20laid%20out%20three%20primary%20reasons%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%201)%20Tariffs%20are%20%26quot%3Bone-off%20increases%20in%20the%20price%20level%26quot%3B%20and%20lead%20to%20only%20temporary%20increases%20in%20inflation.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E2)%20Multiple%20data%20points%20make%20the%20case%20that%20monetary%20policy%20should%20be%20less%20restrictive.%20These%20included%20real%20Gross%20Domestic%20Product%20(GDP)%20growth%2C%20the%20unemployment%20rate%2C%20and%20total%20inflation.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E3)%20While%20the%20labor%20market%20has%20appeared%20%26quot%3Bfine%20on%20the%20surface%2C%26quot%3B%20Waller%20said%20that%20%26quot%3Bother%20data%20suggest%20that%20the%20downside%20risks%20to%20the%20labor%20market%20have%20increased.%26quot%3B%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20data%20imply%20the%20policy%20rate%20should%20be%20around%20neutral%2C%20which%20the%20median%20FOMC%20participant%20estimates%20is%203%20percent%2C%20and%20not%20where%20we%20are%E2%80%941.25%20to%201.50%20percentage%20points%20above%203%20percent%2C%26quot%3B%20Waller%20said%20in%20his%20statement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%223a40dbfa-a5f2-42c6-9c6d-9709012cfb56%5C%22%3EBowman's%20argument%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EBowman%20also%20argued%20that%20the%20Fed%20should%20reduce%20interest%20rates%20by%2025%20basis%20points.%20In%20her%20argument%2C%20she%20primarily%20focused%20on%20the%20strength%20and%20resilience%20of%20the%20US%20economy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWith%20economic%20growth%20slowing%20this%20year%20and%20signs%20of%20a%20less%20dynamic%20labor%20market%2C%20I%20saw%20it%20as%20appropriate%20to%20begin%20gradually%20moving%20our%20moderately%20restrictive%20policy%20stance%20toward%20a%20neutral%20setting%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBowman%20added%20that%20she%20believes%20such%20action%20would%20serve%20as%20an%20effective%20hedge%20against%20less-than-optimal%20economic%20conditions%20and%20potential%20problems%20in%20the%20labor%20market.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20noted%20that%20while%20the%20unemployment%20rate%20has%20remained%20low%20through%20June%20and%20total%20payroll%20employment%20displayed%20modest%20increases%2C%20the%20labor%20market%20had%20become%20%26quot%3Bless%20dynamic%26quot%3B%20and%20showed%20%26quot%3Bincreasing%20signs%20of%20fragility.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBowman%20also%20highlighted%20concerns%20regarding%20the%20Fed's%20employment%20mandate%2C%20speculating%20that%20if%20conditions%20do%20not%20show%20improvement%20soon%2C%20firms%20may%20be%20forced%20to%20lay%20off%20workers%2C%20a%20trend%20that%20has%20already%20taken%20shape.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAs%20I%20recognize%20that%20economic%20conditions%20are%20shifting%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20added%2C%20%26quot%3BI%20believe%20that%20beginning%20to%20move%20our%20policy%20rate%20at%20a%20gradual%20pace%20toward%20its%20neutral%20level%20will%20help%20maintain%20the%20labor%20market%20near%20full%20employment.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finterest-rates-cuts-fed-governors-dissent-inflation-jobs-waller-bowman-2025-8%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1754059966000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F688cd4a13d5881a51c1e70e9%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finterest-rates-cuts-fed-governors-dissent-inflation-jobs-waller-bowman-2025-8%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20Fed%20opted%20against%20cutting%20rates%2C%20but%20a%20rare%20dissent%20from%20two%20governors%20says%20the%20central%20bank%20risks%20b